caption: Craving more blueberries after getting back from Maine this week, I decided to whip up some fluffy blueberry buttermilk pancakes to go with a quality breakfast for dinner. I used AllRecipe’s Buttermilk Pancakes II but added some organic blueberries to pop in my mouth. On the side was some spicy cheesy scrambled eggs, a healthy portion of bacon and some of Whole Food’s chicken blueberry maple breakfast sausage. I need a nap after this one…

I’ve been short on time this past week and haven’t been able to try any new recipes. To keep mouths watering while I’m gone, here’s a pic of one of my average weekend afternoon fruit smoothies. Blended up is a mix of frozen fruit (strawberries, blueberries, raspberries and bananas), vanilla yogurt and a splash of OJ. Cold, thick and delicious!

I started out with plans for a vegetarian meal tonight, but I had an extra slice of bacon that was just begging to be cooked, so I obliged him and tossed bits of it on top of EatingWell’s Miso-Garlic Roasted Tofu Caesar Salad. In the pile on my plate is a mix of chopped romaine, radicchio and parmesan cheese tossed in a dressing of olive oil, red pepper miso, lemon juice and minced garlic. On top of that sat some roasted tofu tossed in a miso-garlic mix and some croutons made from Whole Foods’ country bread. Delicious, filling and totally going on my ‘please make this again’ list.

I was in the mood for seafood and bacon, so I decided to experiment a little and this is result: Spinach stuffed cod fillets wrapped in bacon. I cooked up a mix of minced garlic, chopped fire roasted tomatoes, spinach, crushed red pepper, parmesan cheese and dill weed then rolled it up into some cod fillets. Once stuffed, I wrapped a couple pieces of black forest bacon around the fish and tossed it in the oven.

Once again I used Trader Joe’s whole wheat pizza dough to make some delicious calzones. This time I stuffed the lil pizza pockets with a dabble of pizza sauce, garlic, red onion, green onions, broccoli, mozzarella and pepperjack cheese. Once packed, I brushed the tops with a bit of egg wash to get things crispy and then let ‘em cook.

Looking for something creamy and filling, I tried EatingWell’s Skillet Tuna Noodle Casserole and got just that. I cooked up a mix of onion, mushrooms, tuna, sweet peas, parmesan cheese and thickened milk, stirred in some cooked eggs noodles, covered the whole pan with panko bread crumbs and more cheese and then let it brown under the broiler. I only varied from the recipe by adding in some dill weed and crushed red pepper. Enough to fill 2 bellies and pack 2 lunches.

I wanted to try something different tonight so I gave EatingWell’s Spinach & Feta Souffle a shot. I folded frothy egg whites into a hot mix of feta cheese, fresh mint, spinach, garlic, crushed red pepper and milk and then tossed it all in the oven. The result was souff-tastic!

I put together EatingWell’s Vegetable Fried Rice again tonight. As usual, I used short grain brown rice instead of instant rice. This time I added in some diced carrots, 1 extra egg and used a healthy portion of Frank’s RedHot sauce. Chewbacca, my wok, did good work tonight!

To get my Summer soup on, I gave The Silver Palate Cookbook’s Greek Lemon Soup a try. I used brown rice instead of white, but other than that I stayed true to the recipe. It was light and healthy, so I decided to pair it with something buttery and cheese filled: my first spanakopita experiment. I made a mix of chopped spinach, feta cheese, parmesan cheese, mozzarella cheese, garlic, salt and crushed red pepper and then folded spoonfuls of it up into sheets of phyllo dough layered with melted butter and baked the goods until they were golden. Flaky fantastic!

I cooked up EatingWell’s Sweet Potato Fritters & Smoky Pinto Beans tonight. The store was out of poblanos so I went for banana peppers this time. To make up for the spice difference in the peppers, I added some extra cayenne pepper and a little more paprika than the recipe called for. Looking forward to leftovers for lunch…

For a Father’s Day feast, I decided to come up with an original recipe. I made a buttery mix of lump crab meat, celery, parsley, garlic, dill, crushed red pepper, parmesan cheese and pimentos and then stuffed it into some thick wild King Salmon fillets. I added some steamed broccoli and Good Eats’ Glazed Carrots on the side and was very satisfied with the outcome.

For dinner tonight I tried out EatingWell’s Sweet Potato, Red Onion & Fontina Tart and was quite pleased with the result. I laid down a base of shredded fontina cheese and topped it with concentric circles of roasted sweet potato and red onion slices. That delicious layering was wrapped up in a rustic homemade walnut-based crust flavored with freshly chopped thyme. Definitely going to reuse this crust in the future.

I gave EatingWell’s Five-Spice Turkey & Lettuce Wraps a try tonight and was fairly pleased with the results. In the lettuce leaves is a mix of ground turkey thigh, brown rice, red pepper, water chestnuts, hoisin sauce and a five-spice mix. I topped everything with some shredded carrot and freshly chopped basil and parsley. A tad messy and bland at first, but delightful once I drizzled on some sweet chilli sauce.

Good Eats’ fish tacos again tonight. I skipped the crema and shredded cabbage this time and used diced roma tomatoes, spinach and shredded sharp cheddar cheese. I topped it with a creamy mix of mashed avocado, sour cream, chili powder, cayenne pepper, onion powder and lime juice.

I wanted to use my spare puff pastry in the freezer this week, so I had a friend over and cooked up Good Eats’ Salmon Turnovers. Wrapped up in the golden brown delicious-ness is a mix of salmon, mushrooms sauteed in butter, short grain brown rice, scallions, parsley, relish and a dash of crushed red pepper. I tossed some pearled couscous and broccoli on the side to make a quality meal.

I whipped up one of my favorite original recipes to pair with our weekly big ass salad tonight: sesame salmon nuggets. I breaded chunks of sockeye salmon in a spicy panko-sesame seed mix and then fried them in my cast iron skillet. Plop those nugs on a massive salad and top it with some homemade chipotle ranch and you’ve got yourself a meal!

I had plans to cook EatingWell’s Black Bean-Salmon Stir Fry tonight, but I had some serious issues with finding the ingredients, so I decided to improvise…a lot. I used sunflower sprouts and sauteed mushrooms instead of mung bean sprouts. I also couldn’t get my mits on any black bean-garlic sauce so I made it work with some roasted garlic sauce and a few other spices. Salmon stir fry success!

For an American holiday, I decided to cook in an American style: I cooked meat over fire! I toasted then ground a garam masala mix and then coated lamb loin chops in the spices before tossing them on the grill. I paired it with a little curry flavored couscous and some cooked balsamic-garlic kale.

For dinner tonight, I prepared EatingWell’s Skillet Gnocchi with Chard & White Beans. I used pre-made gnocchi from Trader Joe’s and fire roasted diced tomatoes in a chipotle blend instead of the italian tomatoes the recipe called for. The mix fit nicely in my cast iron skillet and there will be plenty of leftovers for lunch tomorrow…joy!

For a quick meal tonight, I made a mix of corn, black beans and tomato and then used it on a pizza and a salad. I used some spicy barbecue sauce for the pizza sauce and made it rain with some freshly shredded mozzarella. I put the bean/corn mix on a bed of spinach and then topped it with a quick blueberry vinaigrette.
